		<description><![CDATA[We have been assured that Subaru’s next-generation WRX and STI models—based on the all-new 2012 Impreza, which goes on sale in November—will happen. While we couldn’t squeeze out an exact intro date for the performance versions, you’re going to have to wait a while if you want one: We’ve heard from people who ought to [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://blog.caranddriver.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/2011-Subaru-Impreza-WRX-sedan.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-65934" title="2011 Subaru Impreza WRX sedan" src="http://blog.caranddriver.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/2011-Subaru-Impreza-WRX-sedan-626x382.jpg" alt="" width="626" height="382" /></a></p>
<p>We have been assured that Subaru’s next-generation WRX and STI models—based on the <a href="http://www.caranddriver.com/news/car/11q2/2012_subaru_impreza-auto_shows">all-new 2012 Impreza</a>, which goes on sale in November—will happen. While we couldn’t squeeze out an exact intro date for the performance versions, you’re going to have to wait a while if you want one: We’ve heard from people who ought to know that they won’t arrive for a couple of years (the current models will remain in production until they arrive). The delay will give the regular Impreza time to get its footing in the market, as well as allow Subaru’s suits time to answer internal questions about whether to make the next WRX and STI more mature or keep them visceral rally sleds.</p>
<p><a href="http://blog.caranddriver.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/2012-Subaru-Impreza-four-door.jpg"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-65936" title="2012 Subaru Impreza four-door sedan" src="http://blog.caranddriver.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/2012-Subaru-Impreza-four-door-220x134.jpg" alt="" width="220" height="134" /></a>We’re not really sure why it’s even a matter of consideration: The backlash was so severe the last time Subaru tried to make a WRX for adults—it resulted in the <a href="http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/car/07q3/2008_subaru_impreza_wrx-road_test">disappointing 2008 model</a>—that the company immediately <a href="http://www.caranddriver.com/news/car/08q3/2009_subaru_impreza_wrx_2.5gt-car_news">announced a slew of upgrades</a>, and <a href="http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/car/08q4/2009_subaru_impreza_wrx-short_take_road_test">the differences were dramatic</a> between the 2008 and 2009 WRXs. Horsepower went from 224 to 265, 0-to-60-mph acceleration improved from 5.8 to 4.7 seconds, and chassis changes saw the driving experience go from soggy to sensational.</p>
<p>We’re hopeful Subaru will make the right decision—the first time—this time around. Until then, check back soon for our complete, behind-the-wheel report on the regular-grade Impreza, at which point we should know how suitable a foundation it will be for slideways rally awesomeness.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/caranddriver/blog/~4/HQU4qtoI2oo" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
